  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="rightangletriangle"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">RIGHT-ANGLE TRIANGLE</dt>
  <dd>See �<a href="vxt-dvt4.html#triangularpanel">triangular panel 2)</a>&rsquo;). <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4188.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4188.gif" alt="right-angle triangle" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br /><em>National Flag of <a href="pg.html">Papua New Guinea </a> (fotw)</em> 
    
  <hr /><a name="righthoisted"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">RIGHT-HOISTED</dt>
  <dd>A term that may be used (in place of its heraldic equivalent) when the obverse of a 
  flag is depicted (or is manufactured) with its hoist to the observer&rsquo;s right in accordance 
  with Arabic tradition � but see 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs4.html#sinisterhoist">sinister hoist</a>&rsquo; and the note below (also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvh4.html#hoist">hoist 1)</a>&rsquo;, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-o.html#obverse">obverse</a>&rsquo; 
  and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr2.html#reverse">reverse</a>&rsquo;). <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1362.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1362.gif" alt="right-hoisted" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br /><em>National Flag of <a href="qa.html">Qatar</a> (fotw)</em> 
  <p><em>Please note that the Editors recommend use of the heraldic term as being more 
  accurate and will avoid any potential confusion.</em> </dd>
  
  <hr/><a name="riksbanner"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">RIKSBANNER (or RIJKSVAANDEL)</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc8.html#coronationflags">coronation flags</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1350.jpg">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1350.jpg" alt="Riksbanner" border="0" width="114" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Riksbanner/coronation Flag, Norway 1906 (Official Website) </em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="ring"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">RING </dt>
  <dd>1) On flags a charge in the form of a narrow circular band typically (but 
  by no means exclusively) used to separate a sun�s central disc from its rays, 
  as on the flag of Kyrgyzstan (as illustrated below) &ndash; a torus or disc/disk voided (see 
  also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd3.html#disc">disc</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc2.html#cartouche">cartouche</a>&rsquo;). </dd>
  <dd>2) In heraldry see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva3.html#annulet">annulet</a>&rsquo;.</dd>
  <dd>3) A piece of wood or metal for attaching a windsock to its pole and for keeping 
  it open (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvw2.html#windsock">windsock</a>&rsquo;). </dd>
  <dd>4) See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb3.html#battalionring">battalion ring</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb3.html#battlehonor">battle honour</a>&rsquo;.</dd>
  <dd>5) One of a number of circular metal bands used as an increasingly (but 
  not entirely) obsolete method of attaching a military colour, parade flag or 
  gonfalon to its staff - see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc5.html#color">colour 2)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp1.html#paradeflag">parade flag 2)</a>&rsquo; with its following 
  notes and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvg2.html#gonfalon">gonfalon 2)</a>&rsquo;
  (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvl4.html#loop">loops</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt1.html#ties">ties</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4005.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4005.gif" alt="ring" border="0" height="108"/></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4324.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4324.gif" alt="ring" border="0" height="108"/></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1825.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1825.gif" alt="ring" border="0" height="108"/></a> 
  <br />
    <em>National Flag of <a href="kg.html">Kyrgyzstan</a> (fotw);
  Flag of <a href="ch-vd081.html">Bercher</a>, Switzerland (fotw); Flag of the <a href="krd}pkk.html">Kurdish Workers Party</a>, 
  Turkey (fotw) </em>
    
  <hr /><a name="rising"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">RISING</dt>
  <dd>1) In heraldry the term used when a bird is represented as in the act of taking flight 
  (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd3.html#displayed">displayed</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvv2.html#vol">vol</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvv2.html#volant">volant</a>&rsquo;.<br>
  2) In vexillology the term often employed to describe a sun complete with its 
  (usually &ndash; but not invariably &ndash; expanding) rays &ndash; a rising sun (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-r.html#rays">rays</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs8.html#sunburst">sunburst</a>&rsquo;) 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1249b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1249b.gif" alt="[rising example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>&nbsp;
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1249a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1249a.gif" alt="[rising example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4673.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4673.gif" alt="[rising example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br /><em>Flag and Arms of <a href="pl-zp-zl.html">Z&#322;ocieniec</a>, Poland (fotw);
  Flag of the Airforce, The <a href="su^af.html">Soviet Union</a> (fotw)</em>
  </dd>

  <hr /><a name="risingdiag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">RISING DIAGONAL </dt>
  <dd>In heraldry see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva8.html#ascendingdiag">ascending diagonal</a>&rsquo;.<p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d653.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d653.gif" alt="[rising diagonal example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
